Household Goods Online Store Product Analysis¶

Task: to analyze the store's product range, revenue, average check, ARPPU in dynamics for the project managers responsible for the product range to optimize purchases.¶

Articles used:

  1. Bad debt provision definition https://www.accountingtools.com/articles/what-is-a-bad-debt-provision.html#:~:text=A%20bad%20debt%20provision%20is,accounts%20receivable%20as%20being%20uncollectible.&text=These%20adjustments%20may%20lead%20to,in%20the%20bad%20debt%20expense.
  2. Introduction to Market Basket Analysis in Python. https://pbpython.com/market-basket-analysis.html
  3. How to Create Winning Product Assortments in Retail: 6 Tips https://www.vendhq.com/blog/product-assortments/
  4. Association Rules Generation from Frequent Itemsets http://rasbt.github.io/mlxtend/user_guide/frequent_patterns/association_rules/
  5. PRODUCT MIX DECISIONS WIDTH, LENGTH, DEPTH AND CONSISTENCY https://marketing-insider.eu/product-mix-decisions/
  6. Lesson 5. Customize Dates on Time Series Plots in Python Using Matplotlib https://www.earthdatascience.org/courses/use-data-open-source-python/use-time-series-data-in-python/date-time-types-in-pandas-python/customize-dates-matplotlib-plots-python/
  7. A Tutorial About Market Basket Analysis In Python https://predictivehacks.com/a-tutorial-about-market-basket-analysis-in-python/

4. Making reports and calculating metrics

4.1 Analyzing the store's product range: defining trends in categories, sesonality, depth and width of the range (by stock code analysis and extracting categories by the description field).
4.2 Extracting frequent item sets in shopping carts using MLxtend library and Apriori algorythm. Analyzing support, confidence and lift measures. Bundels. Items bought by themselves.
4.3 Analyzing cancelled purchases - products. What is the most frequent types of canceled purchases. How often do they occure?
4.4 Analyzing revenue, average check, ARPPU in dynamics.

5. Formulating and testing hypotheses

6. Conclusion

In the EDA part of the project we have studied each initial column in detail, plotted the distribution graphs.

The majority of the invoices contain more than 1 stock code, meaning that customers buy not one specific thing but rather some set of items. The dataset has 25897 invoices, the biggest purchase of 1114 positions and the smallest - 1 line purchase. There are few variations of the invoice number format - 5 numeric digits, or 5 numeric digits with a letter, wich stands for not a purchase transaction such as cancellation or adjusting bad depth. Sometimes regular 5 digit invoice numbers stand for side transactions, but there is no logic behind that can help to fish such occurances.

There are 4069 unique stock codes for the items, the best-seller is the item with the stock code 85123A - sold 2301 times. The stock codes also have few ways of structure. There are regular stock codes having 5 numeric digits structure and stock codes with the letters. There are 300 stock codes that have more than 1 variation. In most cases it is a color variation of the item. In case of 24 variation stock code - it is different letters of the same letter key ring. The stock codes that are not standing for purchases - such as POST, Discount and other were dropped from the dataset.

In the quantity column we've got positive and negative values: positive are purchases and negative are returns. Percentage of cancelled transactions stands on 1.91%. 95% of the invoices have up to 800 items purchased. There are a lot of big shoppers in this store. The majority of returns had up to 75 items. There is an item "paper craft little birdie" that was ordered in quantity of 80995 items and few min afterwords returned in the same quantity.

The data contains the info on sales from 29th of November, 2018 till 7th of December, 2019. 305 days of obseravtion in total. The number of transactions per day increases with the time.

The store specializes on the cheaper products - the mean price per unit stands on 3.3. 99% of the products cost up to 17. The minimum price per item is 0.03. The maximum price is 649.

We have added new columns to the dataframe that will be usefull in the next section of the project: revenue, week day and hour of transaction.

Making reports and calculating metrics ¶

4.1 Analyzing the store's product range: defining trends in categories, sesonality, depth and width of the range by stock code analysis and extracting categories by the description field.

Product categories: ¶

Our first attempt was to build categories of the products using internal data only - creating keywords from the description field and counting the most popular ones. But we were not satisfied with the results, it was not possible to build comprehensive system of categorization, so we decided to proceed with another approach, using outside sources for categorization. But we will leave this part of the code, may be it can be usefull ones for other purposes.

In [83]:
def find_noun(keyword):
    #print(keyword)
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(keyword)
    tagged = nltk.pos_tag(tokens)
    noun = [w for w,t in tagged if "NN" in t]
    return noun
In [84]:
data['keywords'] = data['description'].apply(find_noun)
In [85]:
keywords = data['keywords'].tolist()

Building categories using Amazon web page parsing

In order to build the comprehensive system of product categorization we decided to use Amazon web-store categories. First we used Scrapy - a fast high-level web crawling and web scraping framework, used to crawl websites and extract structured data from their pages. It can be used for a wide range of purposes, from data mining to monitoring and automated testing (https://scrapy.org/). This framework parsed Amazon web site and added a sub-category for each of the product description from our dataframe. Then we build a dictionary of categories containing almost all the subcategories (the minor ones were gathered by the category "Other"). Then dataframe of categories was merged with out initial dataframe according to the stock code.

# Convert the units to 1 hot encoded values
def encode_units(x):
    if x <= 0:
        return 0
    if x >= 1:
        return 1

Product categories:

After defining product categories using Amazon web store segmentation, we've got 24 big categories of items. The most popular category is "Kitchen". Then comes "Decor" and "Toys & Games" categories.

The most popular products:
The top sold products are white hanging heart t-light holder sold 2248 times, jumbo bag red retrospot - sold 2112 times and regency cake stand 3 tier - 2009 times.
In terms of quantity the most sold items are paper craft little birdie 80995 units which was immidiatly returned. The medium ceramic top storage jar was sold in 78033 units, world war 2 gliders asstd designs 54951 units, and again jumbo bag red retrospot - 48375 units (perhaps to put all the purchases).

Seasonality:

The time analysis revealed that on the worst day the store had 11 customers and on it's best - 214 customers. Seems like late autumn brings more people to the store. We might assume that there are more customers and revenue is higher in the autumn, but we need more observations in order to make conclusion on seasonal trends.

Product breadth and width:

Product breadth: the store offers 3386 different line products.
Product width: the store has 300 products with more than one variation.
The revenue from the products with several variations is a bit lower than from the products with only one variation. Seems like the customers value the breadth of the assortment more than the depth.

Frequent categories combination:

The Apriori algorythm helped us to build the most frequent combinations in the customers' baskets: "Toys & Games" with "Arts & Crafts" and vice versa, "Office" with "Decor and Kitchen" and vice versa; "Decor and Kitchen" with "Arts and Crafts" and vice versa.

Top solo sold items:

The solo sold leaders are: rabbit night light, chili lights, regency cake stand 3 tier.

Cancelled purchases and returns:

Returns happen almost everyday - 302 days out of 305 days of observation.
Usually daily returns are under 500 (money) in total.
The most returned item is medium ceramic top storage jar and rotating silver angels t-light holder. We have defined the return rate of the items (number of returns to number of purchases). The most returned items relative to the number of their purchases are rotating silver t-light holder, black cherry lights, crochet rose des clothes hanger.

KPIs:

Revenue
The highest revenue the store gets on Thursdays. There are no transactions on Saturdays. It can be so because od the bookkeeping system of the store. On 16th of August, 2019 the shop was opened earlier and there were some returnes processed. Usually customers start to buy after 7 o'clock.
All the items were purchased between 8 AM and 8 PM. Or it is the speciality of the book keeping, or it strange online store that has working hours. The highest revenue is at 10 AM and 12 PM. 99% of invoices are not higher than 4397.
Average check
The average revenue per check is around 300. It is going up with the time.
The number of items per check definetly goes up with time. In the beginning it used to be between 100 and 150. By the end of 2019 it is between 150 and 200.
ARPPU
The ARPPU also goes up with time. It started between 250 and 500 and by the end of 2019 it is more 400 to 600.

5. Formulating and testing hypothesis ¶

In the product categories analysis we have defined two most popular categorues: "Kitchen" and "Decor". We will test the hypothesis that the average revenues of these categories are the same.

H0: the average revenue from the items belonging to the "Kitchen" and "Decor" categories is the same.

H1: the average revenue from the items belonging to the "Kitchen" and "Decor" categories is different.

The alpha will be set to 0.05 as the most common in the industry.

In [166]:
sample_1 = data_Kitchen['revenue']
sample_2 = data_Decor['revenue']

alpha = 0.05
                        
results = st.ttest_ind(
        sample_1, 
        sample_2, equal_var = False)

print('p-value: ', results.pvalue)

if (results.pvalue < alpha):
    print("We reject the null hypothesis")
else:
    print("We can't reject the null hypothesis")

p-value:  0.030465390206244825
We reject the null hypothesis

We reject the null hypothesis: the average revenue from the "Kitchen" and "Decor" items is different.

In the product categories analysis we have defined two most popular categorues: "Kitchen" and "Decor". We will test the hypothesis that the average revenues of these categories are the same. We reject the null hypothesis: the average revenue from the "Kitchen" and "Decor" items is different.

6. Conclusion: ¶

Our task in this project was to analyze the store's product range, revenue, average check, ARPPU in dynamics for the project managers responsible for the product range to optimize purchases. For the analysis we've got a dataset of 541909 rows of the transactions from the store. In the preprocessing part we changed the data types in the columns, dealed with the missing values in the description, customer id and price per unit columns. They were filled where possible according to the stock code and invoice date columns. The duplicated rows were dropped as they were considered as a bug in the recording process.

EDA:

In the EDA part of the project we have studied each initial column in detail, plotted the distribution graphs.
The majority of the invoices contain more than 1 stock code, meaning that customers buy not one specific thing but rather some set of items. The dataset has 25897 invoices, the biggest purchase of 1114 positions and the smallest - 1 line purchase. There are few variations of the invoice number format - 5 numeric digits, or 5 numeric digits with a letter, which stands for not a purchase transaction such as cancellation or adjusting bad depth. Sometimes regular 5 digit invoice numbers stand for side transactions, but there is no logic behind that can help to fish such occurrences.
The EDA showed that there are 4069 unique stock codes for the items, the best-seller is the item with the stock code 85123A - sold 2301 times. The stock codes also have few ways of structure. There are regular stock codes having 5 numeric digits structure and stock codes with the letters. There are 300 stock codes that have more than 1 variation. In most cases it is a color variation of the item. In case of 24 variation stock code - it is different letters of the same letter key ring. The stock codes that are not standing for purchases - such as POST,Discount and other were dropped from the dataset.
In the quantity column we've got positive and negative values: positive are purchases and negative are returns. Percentage of cancelled transactions stands on 1.91%. 95% of the invoices have up to 800 items purchased. There are a lot of big shoppers in this store. The majority of returns had up to 75 items. There is an item "paper craft little birdie" that was ordered in quantity of 80995 items and few min afterwords returned in the same quantity.
The data contains the info on sales from 29th of November, 2018 till 7th of December, 2019. 305 days of observation in total. The number of transactions per day increases with the time.The store specializes on the cheaper products - the mean price per unit stands on 3.3. 99% of the products cost up to 17. The minimum price per item is 0.03. The maximum price is 649.
We have added new columns to the dataframe that for the reporting section of the project: revenue, week day and hour of transaction.

The report section:

Product categories:

After defining product categories using Amazon web store segmentation, we've got 24 big categories of items. The most popular category is "Kitchen". Then comes "Decor" and "Toys & Games" categories.

The most popular products:
The top sold products are white hanging heart t-light holder sold 2248 times, jumbo bag red retrospot - sold 2112 times and regency cake stand 3 tier - 2009 times.
In terms of quantity the most sold items are paper craft little birdie 80995 units which was immidiatly returned. The medium ceramic top storage jar was sold in 78033 units, world war 2 gliders asstd designs 54951 units, and again jumbo bag red retrospot - 48375 units (perhaps to put all the purchases).

Seasonality:

The time analysis revealed that on the worst day the store had 11 customers and on its best - 214 customers. Seems like late autumn brings more people to the store. We might assume that there are more customers and revenue is higher in the autumn, but we need more observations in order to make conclusion on seasonal trends.

Product breadth and width:

Product breadth: the store offers 3386 different line products.
Product width: the store has 300 products with more than one variation.
The revenue from the products with several variations is a bit lower than from the products with only one variation. Seems like the customers value the breadth of the assortment more than the depth.

Frequent categories combination:

The Apriori algorithm helped us to build the most frequent combinations in the customers' baskets: "Toys & Games" with "Arts & Crafts" and vice versa, "Office" with "Decor and Kitchen" and vice versa; "Decor and Kitchen" with "Arts and Crafts" and vice versa.

Top solo sold items:

The solo sold leaders are: rabbit night light, chili lights, regency cake stand 3 tier.

Cancelled purchases and returns:

Returns happen almost everyday - 302 days out of 305 days of observation.
Usually daily returns are under 500 (money) in total.
The most returned item is medium ceramic top storage jar and rotating silver angels t-light holder. We have defined the return rate of the items (number of returns to number of purchases). The most returned items relative to the number of their purchases are rotating silver t-light holder, black cherry lights, crochet rose des clothes hanger.

KPIs:

Revenue
The highest revenue the store gets on Thursdays. There are no transactions on Saturdays. It can be so because of the bookkeeping system of the store. On 16th of August, 2019 the shop was opened earlier and there were some returns processed. Usually customers start to buy after 7 o'clock.
All the items were purchased between 8 AM and 8 PM. Or it is the speciality of the book keeping, or it strange online store that has working hours. The highest revenue is at 10 AM and 12 PM. 99% of invoices are not higher than 4397.
Average check
The average revenue per check is around 300. It is going up with the time.
The number of items per check definetly goes up with time. In the beginning it used to be between 100 and 150. By the end of 2019 it is between 150 and 200.
ARPPU
The ARPPU also goes up with time. It started between 250 and 500 and by the end of 2019 it is more 400 to 600.

Testing hypothesis:

In the product categories analysis we have defined two most popular categorues: "Kitchen" and "Decor". We will test the hypothesis that the average revenues of these categories are the same. We reject the null hypothesis: the average revenue from the "Kitchen" and "Decor" items is different.

Recomendations:

We would recommend to rely on the categories analysis and make special offers and promotions in less popular categories in order to increase their sales.
As we've learnt from the categories combinations analysis - there are sets that work well together: "Toys & Games" with "Arts & Crafts", "Office" with "Decor and Kitchen", "Decor and Kitchen" with "Arts and Crafts". It will be good to make special offers when customer adds items from one of these sets to the cart, so he/she has motivation to take more.
For the items that sell well by themselves some bundle offers can be introduced, so people take more.
It is worth learning the reason why the most returned items do not satisfy the customers and improve them or change.
The data on busy days and hours can serve to introduce special deals to increase sales at successful times and improve the purchases on less busy hours.
Seasonal campaigns should help to attract more customers not only in autumn, but also in winter, spring and summer.
